column5: {50094: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "50094",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1557",\\n    "Technique name": "Adversary-in-the-Middle",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to position themselves between two or more networked devices using an adversary-in-the-middle (AiTM) technique to support follow-on behaviors such as Network Sniffing, Transmitted Data Manipulation, or replay attacks (Exploitation for Credential Access)"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects an HTTP attack attempt by the Responder tool, which performs an AiTM attack by poisoning the browser cache and redirecting requests to a malicious server controlled by the adversary."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {38563: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "38563",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1036",\\n    "Technique name": "Masquerading",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to manipulate features of their artifacts to make them appear legitimate or benign to users and/or security tools"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects a Trojan (GateKeylogger) that masquerades as a \\\'404 Not Found\\\' error message to disguise its communication with a command and control server. column5: {1129: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "1129",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1083",\\n    "Technique name": "File and Directory Discovery",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may enumerate files and directories or may search in specific locations of a host or network share for certain information within a file system"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects attempts to access the .htaccess file, which is used for directory-level configuration in Apache web servers. Accessing this file could allow an attacker to enumerate files and directories on the web server, which aligns with the File and Directory Discovery technique."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "1129", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1170",\\n    "Technique name": "Browser Extensions",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may abuse browser extensions and plugins to bypass web browser security policies or load malicious code that appears as user-approved.",".htaccess files can be used to enable or disable browser extensions and plugins on a directory level."],\\n    "Explanation": "While the primary purpose of this rule is to detect File and Directory Discovery, attempts to access the .htaccess file could also be used to enable or disable browser extensions and plugins, which relates to the Browser Extensions technique."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {27967: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "27967",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1505",\\n    "Technique name": "Server Software Component",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may abuse legitimate extensible development features of servers to establish persistent access to systems"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects activity related to the Chopper web shell, which is a malicious server software component that allows remote code execution on the compromised server. column5: {29869: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "29869",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1566",\\n    "Technique name": "Phishing",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may send phishing messages to gain access to victim systems\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects a phishing attack by the Napolar Trojan, which likely involves sending malicious emails or messages to trick users into executing malware disguised as a legitimate Facebook application (facebook.com.exe)."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "29869", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1036",\\n    "Technique name": "Masquerading",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to manipulate features of their artifacts to make them appear legitimate or benign to users and/or security tools\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Trojan is masquerading as a legitimate Facebook application (facebook.com.exe) to appear benign and trick users into executing it."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {31807: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "31807",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1041",\\n    "Technique name": "Exfiltration Over C2 Channel",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may steal data by exfiltrating it over an existing command and control channel"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects a Trojan named Nighthunter attempting to exfiltrate data over the SMTP protocol, which could be used as a command and control channel for data exfiltration."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "31807", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1048",\\n    "Technique name": "Exfiltration Over Alternative Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may steal data by exfiltrating it over a different protocol than that of the existing command and control channel"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for data exfiltration attempts using the SMTP protocol, which is an alternative protocol that could be used for exfiltration instead of the primary command and control channel."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {58751: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "58751",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1190",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploit Public-Facing Application",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to exploit a weakness in an Internet-facing host or system to initially access a network"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects attempts to exploit the Log4j vulnerability in Apache servers that are exposed to the internet and listening on the SMTP port 25. column5: {36100: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "36100",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1078",\\n    "Technique name": "Valid Accounts",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may obtain and abuse credentials of existing accounts as a means of gaining Initial Access, Persistence, Privilege Escalation, or Defense Evasion"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects an attempt to authenticate to the ManageEngine OpManager web application using the default \\\'IntegrationUser\\\' account credentials, which could allow an adversary to gain initial access or elevate privileges."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "36100", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1110",\\n    "Technique name": "Brute Force",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may use brute force techniques to gain access to accounts when passwords are unknown or when password hashes are obtained"],\\n    "Explanation": "While not explicitly stated, this rule could also be triggered by brute force attempts against the \\\'IntegrationUser\\\' account, as it looks for the specific username/password combination used by default."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {10096: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "10096",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1056",\\n    "Technique name": "Input Capture",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may use methods of capturing user input to obtain credentials or collect information"],\\n    "Explanation": "This Snort rule detects activity related to a known keylogger malware (win32.remotekeylog.b) that captures user input (keystrokes) on the infected system. The rule looks for the string \\\'KEY\\\' in network traffic from the local host on port 456, which is a common port used by this keylogger to exfiltrate captured keystrokes. This directly maps to the \\\'Input Capture\\\' technique (T1056) from MITRE ATT&CK."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {47639: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "47639",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1048",\\n    "Technique name": "Exfiltration Over Alternative Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may steal data by exfiltrating it over a different protocol than that of the existing command and control channel"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects potential data exfiltration over DNS by looking for large DNS TXT response records, which could be used to tunnel data over an alternative protocol (DNS) to avoid detection."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "47639", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1572",\\n    "Technique name": "Protocol Tunneling",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may tunnel network communications to and from a victim system within a separate protocol to avoid detection/network filtering and/or enable access to otherwise unreachable systems"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is specifically looking for indicators of DNS tunneling, where data is encapsulated within DNS traffic to bypass security controls or gain access to restricted networks."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {26353: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "26353",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1614",\\n    "Technique name": "System Location Discovery",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may gather information in an attempt to calculate the geographical location of a victim host\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects attempts to check the public IP address of the system by querying checkip.dyndns.org, which is a common technique used by malware to determine the system\\\'s external IP address and potentially its geographical location."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "26353", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1016",\\n    "Technique name": "System Network Configuration Discovery",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may look for details about the network configuration and settings, such as IP and/or MAC addresses, of systems they access or through information discovery of remote systems\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "By querying checkip.dyndns.org, the malware is attempting to discover the system\\\'s external IP address, which is part of the network configuration information."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {37313: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "37313",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1048",\\n    "Technique name": "Exfiltration Over Alternative Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may steal data by exfiltrating it over a different protocol than that of the existing command and control channel\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects attempts to exfiltrate data over the SMTP protocol, which is an alternative protocol to the typical command and control channel. column5: {60401: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "60401",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1505",\\n    "Technique name": "Server Software Component",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may abuse legitimate extensible development features of servers to establish persistent access to systems"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects an attempt to connect to a PHP web shell named DToolPro, which is a malicious server software component that allows remote code execution on the compromised server."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "60401", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1059",\\n    "Technique name": "Command and Scripting Interpreter",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may abuse command and script interpreters to execute commands, scripts, or binaries"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule looks for the \\\'?&cmd=\\\' parameter in the HTTP request, which is used by the DToolPro web shell to pass commands to the server\\\'s command interpreter for execution."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {56600: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56600",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects outbound HTTP connections from the internal network to external servers, which could be an attempt by malware to communicate with a command and control server using the application layer protocol HTTP. This technique allows the malware to blend in with normal web traffic and evade detection."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56600", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1008",\\n    "Technique name": "Fallback Channels",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may use fallback or alternate communication channels if the primary channel is compromised or inaccessible in order to maintain reliable command and control and to avoid data transfer thresholds\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule looks for connections to multiple URLs (/check, /v1/stats, /gql, etc.), which could indicate the malware is attempting to use fallback or alternate communication channels to maintain command and control in case the primary channel is unavailable."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {56598: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56598",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1090",\\n    "Technique name": "Proxy",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may use a connection proxy to direct network traffic between systems or act as an intermediary for network communications to a command and control server to avoid direct connections to their infrastructure"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule appears to be detecting inbound connections from a backdoor trojan named CSBundle_Original, which may be using a proxy or intermediary system to communicate with its command and control server, as indicated by the \\\'inbound connection attempt\\\' message."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56598", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for specific HTTP traffic patterns that may indicate the CSBundle_Original backdoor communicating over the application layer protocol HTTP, potentially to blend in with normal web traffic."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {41435: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "41435",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1197",\\n    "Technique name": "BITS Jobs",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may abuse BITS jobs to persistently execute code and perform various background tasks\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects outbound connections from a Windows system where the User-Agent header is spoofed to appear as the Background Intelligent Transfer Service (BITS), which is commonly abused by malware like the Oilrig Trojan to execute code and maintain persistence."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "41435", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1036",\\n    "Technique name": "Masquerading",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to manipulate features of their artifacts to make them appear legitimate or benign to users and/or security tools\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule also indicates that the malware is masquerading its network traffic to appear as legitimate Google traffic by including the \\\'Referer: https://www.google.com\\\' header, which is a technique used by adversaries to evade detection."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {34037: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "34037",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1036",\\n    "Technique name": "Masquerading",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to manipulate features of their artifacts to make them appear legitimate or benign to users and/or security tools\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects an outbound HTTP connection from an infected host to an external server, where the malware (Dridex trojan) attempts to masquerade its traffic by setting the \\\'Referer\\\' header to a legitimate website (https://twitter.com). column5: {50463: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "50463",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1003",\\n    "Technique name": "OS Credential Dumping",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to dump credentials to obtain account login and credential material, normally in the form of a hash or a clear text password, from the operating system and software"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects attempts to use the Mimikatz tool to dump password hashes from the LSASS (Local Security Authority Subsystem Service) process memory over SMB. Mimikatz is a well-known credential dumping tool that can extract plaintext passwords, hashes, and Kerberos tickets from memory."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "50463", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1550",\\n    "Technique name": "Use Alternate Authentication Material",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may use alternate authentication material, such as password hashes, Kerberos tickets, and application access tokens, in order to move laterally within an environment and bypass normal system access controls"],\\n    "Explanation": "By dumping password hashes using Mimikatz, an adversary can obtain alternate authentication material (password hashes) that can be used for lateral movement and privilege escalation within the compromised environment."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {19706: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "19706",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects outbound HTTP traffic from a known Trojan variant, which uses the application layer protocol HTTP to communicate and blend in with normal web traffic."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "19706", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1008",\\n    "Technique name": "Fallback Channels",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may use fallback or alternate communication channels if the primary channel is compromised or inaccessible in order to maintain reliable command and control and to avoid data transfer thresholds"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for a specific Trojan variant that may be using an alternate communication channel (HTTP) for command and control if the primary channel is unavailable."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {47401: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "47401",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1572",\\n    "Technique name": "Protocol Tunneling",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may tunnel network communications to and from a victim system within a separate protocol to avoid detection/network filtering and/or enable access to otherwise unreachable systems\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects attempts to tunnel HTTP traffic over ICMP, which is a technique used by adversaries to bypass network security controls and maintain covert communication channels."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "47401", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1001",\\n    "Technique name": "Data Obfuscation",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may obfuscate command and control traffic to make it more difficult to detect\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "Tunneling HTTP over ICMP is a form of data obfuscation, as it hides the true nature of the traffic from network monitoring tools."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {44475: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "44475",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1036",\\n    "Technique name": "Masquerading",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to manipulate features of their artifacts to make them appear legitimate or benign to users and/or security tools"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects a malware called GHBkdr that attempts to spoof a TLS handshake with Microsoft.com during the initial connection, likely to masquerade as legitimate traffic and evade detection."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "44475", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1573",\\n    "Technique name": "Encrypted Channel",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may employ a known encryption algorithm to conceal command and control traffic rather than relying on any inherent protections provided by a communication protocol"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for specific byte patterns in the TLS handshake that indicate the malware is attempting to establish an encrypted channel, likely for command and control purposes while obfuscating the traffic."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {59929: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "59929",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1505",\\n    "Technique name": "Server Software Component",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may abuse legitimate extensible development features of servers to establish persistent access to systems"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects attempts to download the Behinder web shell, which is a malicious JSP file that can be uploaded to a web server to gain persistent access and remote code execution capabilities on the compromised system. The rule looks for specific patterns in the JSP code that are indicative of the Behinder web shell, such as the use of Java class loaders and AES encryption. This aligns with the technique of abusing server software components to establish persistent access."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "59929", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1608",\\n    "Technique name": "Stage Capabilities",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may upload, install, or otherwise set up capabilities that can be used during targeting"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Behinder web shell is a capability that can be staged on a compromised web server to enable further malicious activities. By detecting its download attempt, this rule aims to prevent the staging of this capability, which aligns with the T1608 technique."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {50106: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "50106",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1557",\\n    "Technique name": "Adversary-in-the-Middle",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to position themselves between two or more networked devices using an adversary-in-the-middle (AiTM) technique to support follow-on behaviors such as Network Sniffing, Transmitted Data Manipulation, or replay attacks (Exploitation for Credential Access)"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects an attempt by the Responder tool to perform an Adversary-in-the-Middle attack by poisoning the SMB protocol and intercepting traffic between devices on the network."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {43289: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "43289",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1087",\\n    "Technique name": "Account Discovery",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to get a listing of valid accounts, usernames, or email addresses on a system or within a compromised environment"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects an attempt to access the /etc/shadow file, which contains hashed passwords for user accounts on Unix-based systems. This activity is indicative of an adversary attempting to discover valid accounts on the compromised system, which aligns with the Account Discovery technique."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "43289", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1083",\\n    "Technique name": "File and Directory Discovery",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may enumerate files and directories or may search in specific locations of a host or network share for certain information within a file system"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule also relates to the File and Directory Discovery technique, as the adversary is attempting to access a specific file (/etc/shadow) on the target system, which involves enumerating and searching for files of interest."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {28932: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "28932",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1203",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploitation for Client Execution",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may exploit software vulnerabilities in client applications to execute code"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects an attempt to load a CHM (Compiled HTML Help) file, which could potentially exploit a vulnerability in Microsoft Internet Explorer to execute code on the client system. column5: {12775: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "12775",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1203",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploitation for Client Execution",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may exploit software vulnerabilities in client applications to execute code"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects an attempt to exploit a vulnerability in the RealNetworks RealPlayer ActiveX control (Ierpplug.dll) by obfuscating the exploit code. This is an example of exploiting a client-side application vulnerability to achieve code execution on the target system."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "12775", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1027",\\n    "Technique name": "Obfuscated Files or Information",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to make an executable or file difficult to discover or analyze by encrypting, encoding, or otherwise obfuscating its contents on the system or in transit"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule specifically mentions that the exploit code for the RealPlayer vulnerability is obfuscated, likely to evade detection. This aligns with the Obfuscated Files or Information technique where adversaries obfuscate malicious content to make it harder to detect or analyze."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {36666: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "36666",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects outbound HTTP connections from an infected host to a malicious command and control server, indicating the use of the application layer protocol HTTP for communication, likely to blend in with normal web traffic."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "36666", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1008",\\n    "Technique name": "Fallback Channels",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may use fallback or alternate communication channels if the primary channel is compromised or inaccessible in order to maintain reliable command and control and to avoid data transfer thresholds"],\\n    "Explanation": "While not explicitly stated, the rule may be detecting a fallback or alternate command and control channel used by the malware to maintain communication in case the primary channel is unavailable."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {34944: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "34944",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1552",\\n    "Technique name": "Unsecured Credentials",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may search compromised systems to find and obtain insecurely stored credentials"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects an attempt to disclose credentials from the Arcserve Unified Data Protection Management application, which aligns with the technique of searching for and obtaining unsecured credentials on compromised systems."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "34944", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1555",\\n    "Technique name": "Credentials from Password Stores",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may search for common password storage locations to obtain user credentials"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for attempts to retrieve backup policies from the Arcserve application, which could potentially expose stored credentials, matching the technique of searching for credentials in password stores."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {38355: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "38355",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1008",\\n    "Technique name": "Fallback Channels",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may use fallback or alternate communication channels if the primary channel is compromised or inaccessible in order to maintain reliable command and control and to avoid data transfer thresholds"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects a variant of the NetWiredRC malware, which is a remote access trojan (RAT) that can establish command and control (C2) communication. column5: {2589: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "2589",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1203",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploitation for Client Execution",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may exploit software vulnerabilities in client applications to execute code"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects an attempt to exploit a vulnerability in the way Microsoft Windows handles Content-Disposition headers, which could allow remote code execution on the client system. column5: {24088: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "24088",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1572",\\n    "Technique name": "Protocol Tunneling",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may tunnel network communications to and from a victim system within a separate protocol to avoid detection/network filtering and/or enable access to otherwise unreachable systems"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects the Bledoor Trojan, which tunnels TCP traffic over ICMP to bypass firewalls and network monitoring. column5: {16268: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "16268",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects communication from an infected host to a command and control server using the HTTP protocol, which is an application layer protocol. The rule looks for a specific URI path (\\\'/tdss/\\\') and the host header \\\'yournewsblog.net\\\', which are indicators of the TDSS malware communicating with its C2 server."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "16268", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1090",\\n    "Technique name": "Proxy",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may use a connection proxy to direct network traffic between systems or act as an intermediary for network communications to a command and control server to avoid direct connections to their infrastructure\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "While the rule does not explicitly mention a proxy, the use of a domain name like \\\'yournewsblog.net\\\' could potentially be a proxy or intermediary used by the malware to communicate with its actual C2 infrastructure, avoiding direct connections to the real C2 server."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {8445: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "8445",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1105",\\n    "Technique name": "Ingress Tool Transfer",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may transfer tools or other files from an external system into a compromised environment"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects attempts to download a malicious RTF file containing an embedded object package, which could be used to transfer malicious tools or code into the target environment."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "8445", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1204",\\n    "Technique name": "User Execution",\\n    "Quotes": ["An adversary may rely upon specific actions by a user in order to gain execution"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for a malicious RTF file that likely requires user interaction (opening the file) to trigger the execution of the embedded malicious code or package."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {32949: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "32949",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1105",\\n    "Technique name": "Ingress Tool Transfer",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may transfer tools or other files from an external system into a compromised environment\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects the download of an executable file disguised as a screensaver, which could be a tool or malware being transferred into the target environment by an adversary."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "32949", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1036",\\n    "Technique name": "Masquerading",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to manipulate features of their artifacts to make them appear legitimate or benign to users and/or security tools\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule specifically mentions that the executable is disguised as a screensaver file, which is an attempt to masquerade the malicious file as a legitimate one to evade detection."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {21318: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "21318",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects outbound HTTP traffic from a known Trojan malware variant, which uses the application layer protocol HTTP to communicate with its command and control server, blending in with normal web traffic to avoid detection."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "21318", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1027",\\n    "Technique name": "Obfuscated Files or Information",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to make an executable or file difficult to discover or analyze by encrypting, encoding, or otherwise obfuscating its contents on the system or in transit\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule looks for base64 encoded data in the HTTP request, which suggests that the malware is obfuscating its communications by encoding the data before sending it over the network."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {50466: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "50466",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1557",\\n    "Technique name": "Adversary-in-the-Middle",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to position themselves between two or more networked devices using an adversary-in-the-middle (AiTM) technique to support follow-on behaviors such as Network Sniffing, Transmitted Data Manipulation, or replay attacks (Exploitation for Credential Access)"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects an attempt by the Responder tool to perform an SMB negotiation attack, which is a type of adversary-in-the-middle attack. column5: {56864: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56864",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1573",\\n    "Technique name": "Encrypted Channel",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may employ a known encryption algorithm to conceal command and control traffic rather than relying on any inherent protections provided by a communication protocol\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects command and control traffic from the GORAT malware, which uses SSL encryption to conceal its communications. column5: {24095: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "24095",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1219",\\n    "Technique name": "Remote Access Software",\\n    "Quotes": ["An adversary may use legitimate desktop support and remote access software to establish an interactive command and control channel to target systems within networks"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects an attempt to download the TeamViewer remote access software installer, which could potentially be used by an adversary to establish remote access and command and control over a compromised system."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "24095", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1105",\\n    "Technique name": "Ingress Tool Transfer",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may transfer tools or other files from an external system into a compromised environment"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for the download of the TeamViewer installer, which is a tool that could be transferred into the target environment by an adversary for malicious purposes."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {50098: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "50098",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1557",\\n    "Technique name": "Adversary-in-the-Middle",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to position themselves between two or more networked devices using an adversary-in-the-middle (AiTM) technique to support follow-on behaviors such as Network Sniffing, Transmitted Data Manipulation, or replay attacks (Exploitation for Credential Access)"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects an HTTP attack attempt by the Responder tool, which is used to perform LLMNR/NBT-NS/mDNS poisoning and NTLM/NTLMv2 relay attacks. column5: {1443: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "1443",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1005",\\n    "Technique name": "Data from Local System",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may search local system sources, such as file systems and configuration files or local databases, to find files of interest and sensitive data prior to Exfiltration"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects an attempt to retrieve the \\\'passwd\\\' file using the TFTP protocol, which is a technique used by adversaries to gather sensitive data from local system sources like configuration files."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "1443", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1552",\\n    "Technique name": "Unsecured Credentials",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may search compromised systems to find and obtain insecurely stored credentials"],\\n    "Explanation": "The \\\'passwd\\\' file contains user account credentials, so this rule is also relevant to the \\\'Unsecured Credentials\\\' technique, where adversaries attempt to find and obtain insecurely stored credentials on compromised systems."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {44474: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "44474",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1573",\\n    "Technique name": "Encrypted Channel",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may employ a known encryption algorithm to conceal command and control traffic rather than relying on any inherent protections provided by a communication protocol"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects malware (GHBkdr) attempting to spoof the TLS Change Cipher message, which is part of the TLS handshake process used to establish an encrypted channel for communication. column5: {56599: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56599",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects outbound HTTP traffic from an infected host to an external server, which could be an attempt by malware to communicate with its command and control server using the application layer protocol HTTP to blend in with normal web traffic."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56599", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1090",\\n    "Technique name": "Proxy",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may use a connection proxy to direct network traffic between systems or act as an intermediary for network communications to a command and control server to avoid direct connections to their infrastructure\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule may be detecting traffic from an infected host to an external server acting as a proxy or intermediary for the malware\\\'s command and control communications, to avoid direct connections to the attacker\\\'s infrastructure."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {48818: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "48818",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects outbound HTTP traffic from an infected host to an external server, which could be an attempt by malware to communicate over an application layer protocol (HTTP) to blend in with normal traffic and avoid detection."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "48818", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1036",\\n    "Technique name": "Masquerading",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to manipulate features of their artifacts to make them appear legitimate or benign to users and/or security tools"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule looks for a specific User-Agent string used by a Trojan variant, which could be an attempt by the malware to masquerade as legitimate traffic to evade detection."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {41920: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "41920",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1110",\\n    "Technique name": "Brute Force",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may use brute force techniques to gain access to accounts when passwords are unknown or when password hashes are obtained"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects brute force attempts against the McAfee Virus Scan Linux authentication system, specifically targeting the nailsSessionId cookie used for authentication. column5: {33939: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "33939",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1105",\\n    "Technique name": "Ingress Tool Transfer",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may transfer tools or other files from an external system into a compromised environment\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects the transfer of a .cpl (Control Panel) executable file as an email attachment, which could be used by an adversary to deliver malicious tools or payloads to a compromised system."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "33939", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1204",\\n    "Technique name": "User Execution",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'An adversary may rely upon specific actions by a user in order to gain execution\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for a user action of opening a malicious .cpl file attachment, which could lead to code execution on the user\\\'s system."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {34709: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "34709",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1499",\\n    "Technique name": "Endpoint Denial of Service",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may perform Endpoint Denial of Service (DoS) attacks to degrade or block the availability of services to users"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects an attempt to perform a denial of service attack against the Kerberos authentication service, which would disrupt authentication for endpoints on the network."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "34709", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1558",\\n    "Technique name": "Steal or Forge Kerberos Tickets",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to subvert Kerberos authentication by stealing or forging Kerberos tickets to enable Pass the Ticket"],\\n    "Explanation": "While this rule specifically looks for a denial of service attempt against Kerberos, disrupting the Kerberos authentication service could be a precursor to stealing or forging Kerberos tickets for lateral movement."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {18329: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "18329",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1047",\\n    "Technique name": "Windows Management Instrumentation",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may abuse Windows Management Instrumentation (WMI) to execute malicious commands and payloads"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects attempts to access the Microsoft Windows WMI Administrator Tools Object Viewer ActiveX control, which can be used to execute arbitrary code via WMI. column5: {27919: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "27919",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1020",\\n    "Technique name": "Automated Exfiltration",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may exfiltrate data, such as sensitive documents, through the use of automated processing after being gathered during Collection\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects encrypted POST data exfiltration by the Zeus Trojan, which is an example of automated exfiltration of collected data over an HTTP channel."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "27919", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1041",\\n    "Technique name": "Exfiltration Over C2 Channel",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may steal data by exfiltrating it over an existing command and control channel\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is specifically looking for exfiltration of data over HTTP, which could be used as a command and control channel by malware like Zeus Trojan."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {28323: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "28323",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1505",\\n    "Technique name": "Server Software Component",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may abuse legitimate extensible development features of servers to establish persistent access to systems"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects activity related to the Chopper web shell, which is a malicious server software component that allows adversaries to gain persistent access and control over a compromised system."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "28323", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1090",\\n    "Technique name": "Proxy",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may use a connection proxy to direct network traffic between systems or act as an intermediary for network communications to a command and control server to avoid direct connections to their infrastructure"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule looks for the \\\'X-Forwarded-For\\\' header, which is commonly used by proxy servers to identify the originating IP address of a client. column5: {32001: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "32001",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1573",\\n    "Technique name": "Encrypted Channel",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may employ a known encryption algorithm to conceal command and control traffic rather than relying on any inherent protections provided by a communication protocol"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects inbound SSL traffic from a known malicious domain associated with the Upatre malware, which uses encrypted channels for command and control communication."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "32001", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1090",\\n    "Technique name": "Proxy",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may use a connection proxy to direct network traffic between systems or act as an intermediary for network communications to a command and control server to avoid direct connections to their infrastructure"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule looks for SSL traffic from an external IP to the internal network, which could indicate the use of a proxy or intermediary for command and control communication by the Upatre malware."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {57532: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "57532",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1552",\\n    "Technique name": "Unsecured Credentials",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may search compromised systems to find and obtain insecurely stored credentials"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects an attempt to retrieve backup policies from the Arcserve Unified Data Protection Management service, which could potentially expose unsecured credentials stored within those policies."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "57532", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1213",\\n    "Technique name": "Data from Information Repositories",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may leverage information repositories to mine valuable information"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for attempts to retrieve data from the Arcserve Unified Data Protection Management service, which acts as an information repository containing backup policies and potentially other sensitive data."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {24087: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "24087",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1572",\\n    "Technique name": "Protocol Tunneling",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may tunnel network communications to and from a victim system within a separate protocol to avoid detection/network filtering and/or enable access to otherwise unreachable systems"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects the Bledoor Trojan, which tunnels TCP traffic over UDP to bypass firewalls and network monitoring. The rule looks for specific byte patterns in the UDP payload that indicate encapsulated TCP headers, which is a form of protocol tunneling."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "24087", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1095",\\n    "Technique name": "Non-Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may use an OSI non-application layer protocol for communication between host and C2 server or among infected hosts within a network"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for UDP traffic on port 53 (DNS), which is a non-application layer protocol being misused for command and control communication by the Bledoor Trojan."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {38565: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "38565",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1197",\\n    "Technique name": "BITS Jobs",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may abuse BITS jobs to persistently execute code and perform various background tasks\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects a Trojan (Win.Trojan.Sweeper) attempting to download a malicious file using the BITS (Background Intelligent Transfer Service) protocol, which is commonly abused by malware to execute code and perform tasks in the background."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "38565", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1105",\\n    "Technique name": "Ingress Tool Transfer",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may transfer tools or other files from an external system into a compromised environment\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for an initial download attempt of a malicious binary file (.bin) from an external source, which aligns with the technique of transferring tools or files into a compromised system."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {1882: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "1882",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1033",\\n    "Technique name": "System Owner/User Discovery",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to identify the primary user, currently logged in user, set of users that commonly uses a system, or whether a user is actively using the system"],\\n    "Explanation": "This Snort rule appears to be detecting attempts to retrieve user ID (uid) and group ID (gid) information, which could be used by an adversary to discover system owners or users on the compromised system."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "1882", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1087",\\n    "Technique name": "Account Discovery",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to get a listing of valid accounts, usernames, or email addresses on a system or within a compromised environment"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for traffic containing uid and gid values, which could indicate an attempt by an adversary to discover user accounts on the targeted system."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {2044: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "2044",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1133",\\n    "Technique name": "External Remote Services",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may leverage external-facing remote services to initially access and/or persist within a network"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects attempts to initiate a Point-to-Point Tunneling Protocol (PPTP) connection, which is a remote access protocol used to establish a virtual private network (VPN) connection over the Internet. Adversaries may leverage such external-facing remote services to gain initial access or maintain persistence within a network."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "2044", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1095",\\n    "Technique name": "Non-Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may use an OSI non-application layer protocol for communication between host and C2 server or among infected hosts within a network"],\\n    "Explanation": "PPTP operates at the data link layer (Layer 2) of the OSI model, which is a non-application layer protocol. column5: {42395: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "42395",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1197",\\n    "Technique name": "BITS Jobs",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may abuse BITS jobs to persistently execute code and perform various background tasks\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects outbound connections from the Win.Trojan.Oddjob malware, which uses the Background Intelligent Transfer Service (BITS) to communicate with its command and control server. column5: {28399: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "28399",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1571",\\n    "Technique name": "Non-Standard Port",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may communicate using a protocol and port pairing that are typically not associated"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects outbound connections from the internal network to external IP addresses on ports 6666-7000, which are non-standard ports typically associated with malware command and control traffic."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "28399", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule looks for specific patterns in the IRC protocol, which is an application layer protocol, indicating that the malware is using IRC for command and control communication while attempting to blend in with legitimate traffic."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {1280: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "1280",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1046",\\n    "Technique name": "Network Service Discovery",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to get a listing of services running on remote hosts and local network infrastructure devices, including those that may be vulnerable to remote software exploitation"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects attempts to list services running on the portmapper (port 111), which is a service used to map RPC program numbers to TCP/IP port numbers. This is a form of network service discovery, which adversaries may use to identify potential targets for exploitation."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "1280", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1049",\\n    "Technique name": "System Network Connections Discovery",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to get a listing of network connections to or from the compromised system they are currently accessing or from remote systems by querying for information over the network"],\\n    "Explanation": "While the rule is primarily focused on detecting network service discovery, the portmapper service can also provide information about active network connections, which relates to the System Network Connections Discovery technique."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {19037: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "19037",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects outbound connections from an infected host to an external IRC server on ports 6666-6667, which are commonly used for Internet Relay Chat (IRC). The rule looks for specific patterns in the IRC JOIN command, indicating the use of an application layer protocol (IRC) for command and control communication."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "19037", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1090",\\n    "Technique name": "Proxy",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may use a connection proxy to direct network traffic between systems or act as an intermediary for network communications to a command and control server to avoid direct connections to their infrastructure"],\\n    "Explanation": "The use of an IRC server as a command and control channel can be considered a form of proxy, where the infected host communicates with the attacker\\\'s infrastructure indirectly through the IRC server, potentially obfuscating the true source of the command and control traffic."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {31289: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "31289",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1005",\\n    "Technique name": "Data from Local System",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may search local system sources, such as file systems and configuration files or local databases, to find files of interest and sensitive data prior to Exfiltration"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects attempts to access the /etc/passwd file, which contains sensitive information about user accounts on Unix-based systems. column5: {18242: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "18242",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1047",\\n    "Technique name": "Windows Management Instrumentation",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may abuse Windows Management Instrumentation (WMI) to execute malicious commands and payloads\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects attempts to access the Microsoft Windows WMI Administrator Tools Object Viewer ActiveX control, which can be abused by adversaries to execute malicious commands and payloads via WMI."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "18242", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1211",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploitation for Defense Evasion",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may exploit a system or application vulnerability to bypass security features\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for exploitation of a vulnerability in the Microsoft Windows WMI Administrator Tools Object Viewer ActiveX control, which could allow an adversary to bypass security defenses and execute code."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {41712: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "41712",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1197",\\n    "Technique name": "BITS Jobs",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may abuse BITS jobs to persistently execute code and perform various background tasks\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects a Trojan (Win.Trojan.Houdini) attempting to download a malicious file (ChromeSetup.bat) using the BITS (Background Intelligent Transfer Service) user agent string, which is commonly abused by malware to execute code and perform tasks in the background."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "41712", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1105",\\n    "Technique name": "Ingress Tool Transfer",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may transfer tools or other files from an external system into a compromised environment\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is also detecting the transfer of a malicious file (ChromeSetup.bat) from an external system into the compromised environment, which aligns with the Ingress Tool Transfer technique."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {56613: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56613",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects outbound HTTP traffic from a system infected with the FeyeYelp malware variant, which uses HTTP as an application layer protocol to communicate with its command and control server, blending in with normal web traffic to avoid detection."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56613", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1008",\\n    "Technique name": "Fallback Channels",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may use fallback or alternate communication channels if the primary channel is compromised or inaccessible in order to maintain reliable command and control and to avoid data transfer thresholds"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule looks for specific HTTP cookies and parameters used by the FeyeYelp malware, which could indicate the use of an alternate communication channel if the primary channel is unavailable or compromised."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {50464: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "50464",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1135",\\n    "Technique name": "Network Share Discovery",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may look for folders and drives shared on remote systems as a means of identifying sources of information to gather as a precursor for Collection and to identify potential systems of interest for Lateral Movement\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects an attempt by the Responder tool to enumerate network shares on remote systems by sending a malformed NetServerEnum request over SMB (port 445). This aligns with the Network Share Discovery technique, where adversaries try to discover shared network resources for potential lateral movement or data collection."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "50464", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1018",\\n    "Technique name": "Remote System Discovery",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to get a listing of other systems by IP address, hostname, or other logical identifier on a network that may be used for Lateral Movement from the current system\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Responder tool used in this attack also attempts to discover other systems on the network by responding to various network broadcast requests. column5: {1292: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "1292",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1083",\\n    "Technique name": "File and Directory Discovery",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may enumerate files and directories or may search in specific locations of a host or network share for certain information within a file system\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects attempts to list directory contents by looking for the \\\'Volume Serial Number\\\' string, which is typically part of the output when listing directories on Windows systems. column5: {408: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "408",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1046",\\n    "Technique name": "Network Service Discovery",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to get a listing of services running on remote hosts and local network infrastructure devices, including those that may be vulnerable to remote software exploitation"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects ICMP Echo Reply packets, which can be used by adversaries to discover active hosts and services on a network through techniques like ping sweeps."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "408", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1595",\\n    "Technique name": "Active Scanning",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may execute active reconnaissance scans to gather information that can be used during targeting"],\\n    "Explanation": "ICMP Echo Reply packets are responses to ICMP Echo Request packets, which are commonly used in active scanning techniques like ping sweeps to identify live hosts on a network."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {59502: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "59502",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1210",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploitation of Remote Services",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may exploit remote services to gain unauthorized access to internal systems once inside of a network"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects an attempt to exploit a buffer overflow vulnerability in the Microsoft Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP) service running on Windows Server 2003. column5: {23780: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "23780",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects outbound HTTP traffic from an infected host to an external IP address, which could be an attempt by malware to communicate with a command and control server using the application layer protocol HTTP to blend in with normal web traffic."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "23780", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1090",\\n    "Technique name": "Proxy",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may use a connection proxy to direct network traffic between systems or act as an intermediary for network communications to a command and control server to avoid direct connections to their infrastructure\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule may also be detecting traffic being proxied through an infected host to communicate with a command and control server, as malware often uses proxies to obscure their infrastructure."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}
